That which may truly be said to have led Napier to the invention of Logarithms, is the profound view he took of the Logistic of concrete quantity, after having thoroughly mas- tered that of discrete quantity. The properties of what we may now term the Logarithms of discrete ratios, namely. the series of natural numbers taken to enumerate the steps or terms of any geometrical progression represented by integ-ers, had been known since the days of Archimedes.
